  "opinion": "As a barista in Milan who spends about an hour daily on social media, I’ve learned that managing fake content isn’t about deleting everything but about cultivating critical thinking and mindful engagement. My background—growing up in a family where my dad had a vocational diploma and my mom only went to primary school—taught me to question information sources early on. I remember my mother always saying, 'If it sounds too good to be true, it probably is,' a lesson that’s still useful today. With my high neuroticism score, I can get anxious when I see viral misinformation, especially when it targets my community or involves sensitive topics like health or relationships. But yoga and rock climbing have helped me stay grounded; they teach me to pause before reacting. For instance, when I saw a post claiming a local café’s espresso was 'miraculously' healthier than others, I checked the source and realized it was a paid ad. I shared it with a friend who’s into health, but I made sure to clarify it was promotional. My Christian faith also guides me to approach this with kindness—instead of spreading panic, I encourage others to verify before sharing. In Milan, where social media is a big part of daily life, I’ve found that talking to neighbors or coworkers about these issues helps build trust. It’s not about being perfect but about being intentional. When I see something that makes me uneasy, I ask myself: 'Is this true? Who made it? What’s the purpose?' That simple habit has reduced my anxiety and kept me from spreading false info. Ultimately, managing fake content is like my job—it requires patience, attention to detail, and a bit of humility. I’ve learned that the best way to handle it is not to fight the noise but to find the quiet space to think clearly.",
